To generate “t7 t18”:

1. Use the production S → NT77 NT88.  
2. NT77 → ‘t7’ (given).  
3. NT88 → ‘t18’ (given).  

Thus S ⇒ NT77 NT88 ⇒ ‘t7’ ‘t18’. The string is in the language.  
Yes

We attempt S ⇒ NT77 NT61, with NT77 ⇒ ‘t7’ for the first symbol.  To get the two symbols t18 t10 from NT61, use  

NT61 ⇒ NT88 NT14  
NT88 ⇒ ‘t18’  
NT14 ⇒ ‘t10’  

Hence  
S ⇒ NT77 NT61 ⇒ ‘t7’ (NT88 NT14) ⇒ t7 t18 t10  

So the grammar does generate the string.  
Yes

After checking all possible expansions of S (which are S→NT77 NT88 or S→NT77 NT61) and the ways NT77, NT88, and NT61 can derive terminals, there is no way to get exactly the three-terminal string t34 t17 t12.  
No

After inspecting all possible parses of S:

1. S→NT77 NT88 can only yield two terminals (NT77→t34 or t7; NT88→t18), so it can’t produce a 3‑terminal string.

2. S→NT77 NT61 yields three terminals only when NT61 uses a binary rule that expands to exactly two terminals. The two viable NT61 rules are  
   • NT61→NT88 NT14 ⇒ t18 t10  
   • NT61→NT27 NT16 ⇒ one of {t16,t1} × one of {t39,t46}  

   In each case NT77 produces either t34 or t7 as the first terminal. Thus any 3‑terminal string from S must start with t34 or t7. Our target string starts with t10, so it cannot match.

Hence the grammar does not generate `t10 t16 t46`.  
No

After applying the CYK‐style argument you find that  
1. S → NT77 NT88 produces exactly 2 terminals,  
2. S → NT77 NT61 can produce lengths 2, 3 or ≥5, but never 4,  
and moreover NT77 can only yield t34 or t7 (so it can’t match the initial t46).  
Hence the grammar cannot generate “t46 t1 t34 t25”.  
No

We attempt the production  
S → NT77 NT61  
NT77 → 't7'  
so we match the first token t7. Now NT61 must yield the four‐token sequence t15 t5 t25 t46.  
Look at NT61 → NT27 NT16.  
- NT16 → 't46' gives the final token.  
- NT27 must then yield t15 t5 t25. Use NT27 → NT45 NT7.  
  • NT45 → NT78 NT6 → 't15' 't5' for the next two tokens.  
  • NT7 → 't25' for the next token.  

Putting it all together:  
S → NT77 NT61  
   → 't7' (NT27 NT16)  
   → 't7' (NT45 NT7) NT16  
   → 't7' (NT78 NT6) NT7 NT16  
   → t7 (t15 t5) t25 t46  

which exactly matches t7 t15 t5 t25 t46.  
Yes

so the first terminal of any S‐derivation must come from NT77 (either “t7” or “t34”), but our string begins with “t1.”  No other S‐rule can yield five terminals, so the grammar cannot generate

t1 t15 t15 t17 t10.

Thus the first terminal of any generated string comes from NT77. But NT77 has only these terminal rules:

  NT77 → “t7”  

Our target string begins with “t30”. Since NT77 cannot produce “t30”, no derivation from S can match the input.

We attempt to parse the 11‐token string under S:

1) S→NT77 NT88 forces NT77 to cover token 1 (t7) and NT88 tokens 2–11. But NT88→'t18' covers exactly one token, so impossible.

2) S→NT77 NT61 covers t7 with NT77, leaving 10 tokens for NT61. NT61 has only these length‐lists for its binary productions:

   • NT61→NT43 NT10 ⇒ lengths in {6,7,8}  
   • NT61→NT88 NT14 ⇒ length 2  
   • NT61→NT27 NT16 ⇒ lengths in {3,4,9,10}  

To get length 10, we must use NT27 NT16 with NT27→9 tokens and NT16→1 token. But NT16 only yields t39 or t46, whereas the 11th token is t10. No terminal matches. The other alternatives give wrong lengths. Hence no derivation exists.

and NT77 can only ever produce the single terminals “t34” or “t7” (it has no binary expansions).  Hence any string in L(G) must begin with either t34 or t7.  The given string begins with t14, so it cannot be generated.

We apply the CYK‐style check.  The start rules are

  S → NT77 NT88  
  S → NT77 NT61

1) To cover an 18‐token string, NT77 must take exactly one terminal (it only has NT77→t7 or t34), so it sits over the first token. Our string begins “t7 …”, so NT77→t7 covers position 1.

2) The remaining span (positions 2…18) must be covered by either NT88 or NT61:

   – NT88 only has NT88→'t18', so it can cover exactly one position and only matches “t18”. But position 2 in the string is “t38”, so NT88 cannot cover 2…18.  
   
   – NT61 has three binary expansions  
        NT61→NT43 NT10  
        NT61→NT88 NT14  
        NT61→NT27 NT16  
     and two terminal expansions NT61→t17 or NT61→t38.  
     
     To cover 17 tokens (positions 2…18) NT61 must use one of the binary rules.  But in each case the right child (NT10, NT14 or NT16) can only cover a single terminal—and none of them can match the final token “t38” at position 18 (NT10→t46, NT14→t10, NT16→t39 or t46).  Hence NT61 cannot span positions 2…18.

Since neither S→NT77 NT88 nor S→NT77 NT61 can cover all 18 tokens, the string is not in the language.

After checking, the longest string S can produce is of length at most 10 (via S→NT77 NT61), and there are no recursive cycles that could stretch it to 18 terminals.  Our target string has length 18, so it cannot be generated. No

To see why no derivation is possible, note that S has only two productions:

 1. S → NT77 NT88  
 2. S → NT77 NT61  

NT77 and NT88 both expand in exactly one step to a single terminal (so each has yield‐length 1). Thus S→NT77 NT88 can only ever produce a 2‐symbol string.

The only hope for a longer string is S→NT77 NT61, which yields length = 1 + (length of NT61). But inspecting NT61’s productions:

 • NT61→'t17' or 't38'  → length 1  
 • NT61→NT88 NT14    → length 1+1=2  
 • NT61→NT43 NT10    → length at most 6+1=7  
 • NT61→NT27 NT16    → length at most 9+1=10  

(One checks each right‐hand side by unfolding the finite, acyclic dependencies: no nonterminal ever recurses, so these are strict upper bounds.)

Hence the longest string S can generate is of length 1+10=11 symbols, far short of the 22‐symbol input. Answer: No.

After inspecting the grammar you’ll see there is no way to “grow” a substring beyond constant size—every chain of binary rules bottoms out without recursion, so the longest string S can generate is at most 1 (from NT77) + 10 (max from NT61) = 11 terminals. Since the given input has 23 terminals, it cannot be generated.

We start with S.  The first token is t7, so we must use S→NT77 NT61 with NT77→t7.  That leaves the remaining 24 tokens to be generated by NT61.  But NT61 has only these productions:

 • NT61→NT43 NT10  
 • NT61→NT88 NT14  
 • NT61→NT27 NT16  
 • NT61→t17  
 • NT61→t38  

• NT88→t18 and NT14→t10, so NT88 NT14 would yield exactly “t18 t10” (length 2), but our next two tokens are “t34 t30.”  
• NT43 NT10 would end in NT10→t46, so the last token of its yield is t46, but our 24th token is t10.  
• NT27 NT16 can only yield lengths 2, 5 or 10, never 24.  
• The two terminals t17 or t38 yield length 1.  

NT61 can never produce a 24‐token string, so it cannot cover the tail of length 24.  Hence the grammar cannot generate the given 25‐token string.

We first note that in a CNF grammar every non‐terminal either produces exactly one terminal (length 1) or exactly two non‐terminals (length ≥2).  Since there are no ε‐productions and no recursive cycles, every non‐terminal has a finite maximum yield length.  In particular one checks that

• NT61 can expand in at most 10 terminals (best case NT61→NT27 NT16 with NT27→NT45 NT7→… produces ≤9 then plus NT16).  
• NT88 only ever produces exactly 1 terminal.  
• NT77 only ever produces exactly 1 terminal.  

The start symbol S has only two productions:

  S→NT77 NT88  (total length 2)  
  S→NT77 NT61  (total length ≤1+10=11)

Thus S can generate at most 11 terminals.  The given string has 41 terminals, so it cannot be generated.
